# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: finite-state-machine-ai
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Artificial intelligence (AI) in video games refers to the computational systems that control non-player characters (NPCs), generate dynamic game behavior, or simulate strategic decision-making.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In practice, the term covers a broad range of techniques drawn from computer science, control theory, and robotics rather than "true" artificial intelligence.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Moreover, academic AI—aimed at developing autonomous reasoning or learning—is distinct from game AI, whose goal is to deliver engaging, believable, and efficient behavior for players.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The term *CPU* in video games refer to the AI that control a NPC that could be a playable character in some other situations.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In general, game AI does not, as might be thought and sometimes is depicted to be the case, mean a realization of an artificial person corresponding to an NPC in the manner of the Turing test or an artificial general intelligence.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Some commentators in the video game industry have claimed that advances in game AI have transformed how players interact with digital systems more broadly.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Marketing discussions sometimes attribute human-like traits to game AI—such as personality or creative autonomy—but these are often scripted behaviors designed to mimic complexity rather than emergent cognition.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Game playing was an area of research in AI from its inception.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] One of the first examples of AI is the computerized game of Nim made in 1941 and published in 1942.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Despite being advanced technology in the year it was made, 20 years before *Pong*, the game took the form of a relatively small box and was able to regularly win games even against highly skilled players of the game.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In 1951, using the Ferranti Mark 1 machine of the University of Manchester, Christopher Strachey wrote a checkers program and Dietrich Prinz wrote one for chess.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] These were among the first computer programs ever written.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Arthur Samuel's checkers program, developed in the middle 1950s and early 1960s, eventually achieved sufficient skill to challenge a respectable amateur.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Work on checkers and chess would culminate in the defeat of Garry Kasparov by IBM's Deep Blue computer in 1997.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The first video games developed in the 1960s and early 1970s, like *Spacewar!*, *Pong*, and *Gotcha* (1973), were games implemented on discrete logic and strictly based on the competition of two players, without AI.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Games that featured a single player mode with enemies started appearing in the 1970s.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The first notable ones for the arcade appeared in 1974: the Taito game *Speed Race* (racing video game) and the Atari games *Qwak* (duck hunting light gun shooter) and *Pursuit* (fighter aircraft dogfighting simulator).
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Two text-based computer games, *Star Trek* (1971) and *Hunt the Wumpus* (1973), also had enemies.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Enemy movement was based on stored patterns.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The incorporation of microprocessors would allow more computation and random elements overlaid into movement patterns.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] *Galaxian* (1979) added more complex and varied enemy movements, including maneuvers by individual enemies who break out of formation.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] *Pac-Man* (1980) introduced AI patterns to maze games, with the added quirk of different personalities for each enemy.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] *Karate Champ* (1984) later introduced AI patterns to fighting games.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] *First Queen* (1988) was a tactical action RPG which featured characters that can be controlled by the computer's AI in following the leader.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The role-playing video game *Dragon Quest IV* (1990) introduced a "Tactics" system, where the user can adjust the AI routines of non-player characters during battle, a concept later introduced to the action role-playing game genre by *Secret of Mana* (1993).
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Games like *Madden Football*, *Earl Weaver Baseball* and *Tony La Russa Baseball* all based their AI in an attempt to duplicate on the computer the coaching or managerial style of the selected celebrity.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Madden, Weaver and La Russa all did extensive work with these game development teams to maximize the accuracy of the games.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Later sports titles allowed users to "tune" variables in the AI to produce a player-defined managerial or coaching strategy.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The emergence of new game genres in the 1990s prompted the use of formal AI tools like finite-state machines.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Real-time strategy games taxed the AI with many objects, incomplete information, pathfinding problems, real-time decisions and economic planning, among other things.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The first games of the genre had notorious problems.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] *Herzog Zwei* (1989), for example, had almost broken pathfinding and very basic three-state state machines for unit control, and *Dune II* (1992) attacked the players' base in a beeline and used numerous cheats.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Later games in the genre exhibited more sophisticated AI.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Later games have used bottom-up AI methods, such as the emergent behaviour and evaluation of player actions in games like *Creatures* or *Black & White*.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] *Façade* was released in 2005 and used interactive multiple way dialogs and AI as the main aspect of game.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Games have provided an environment for developing artificial intelligence with potential applications beyond gameplay.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Examples include Watson, a Jeopardy!-playing computer; and the RoboCup tournament, where robots are trained to compete in soccer.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Many experts complain that the "AI" in the term *game AI* overstates its worth, as game AI is not about intelligence, and shares few of the objectives of the academic field of AI.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Whereas "real AI" addresses fields of machine learning, decision making based on arbitrary data input, and even the ultimate goal of strong AI that can reason, "game AI" often consists of a half-dozen rules of thumb, or heuristics, that are just enough to give a good gameplay experience.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Historically, academic game-AI projects have been relatively separate from commercial products because the academic approaches tended to be simple and non-scalable.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Commercial game AI has developed its own set of tools, which have been sufficient to give good performance in many cases.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Game developers' increasing awareness of academic AI and a growing interest in computer games by the academic community is causing the definition of what counts as AI in a game to become less idiosyncratic.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Nevertheless, significant differences between different application domains of AI mean that game AI can still be viewed as a distinct subfield of AI.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In particular, the ability to legitimately solve some AI problems in games by cheating creates an important distinction.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] For example, inferring the position of an unseen object from past observations can be a difficult problem when AI is applied to robotics, but in a computer game a NPC can simply look up the position in the game's scene graph.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Such cheating can lead to unrealistic behavior and so is not always desirable.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] But its possibility serves to distinguish game AI and leads to new problems to solve, such as when and how to cheat.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The major limitation to strong AI is the inherent depth of thinking and the extreme complexity of the decision-making process.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] This means that although it would be then theoretically possible to make "smart" AI the problem would take considerable processing power.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Game AI/heuristic algorithms are used in a wide variety of quite disparate fields inside a game.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The most obvious is in the control of any NPCs in the game, although "scripting" (decision tree) is currently the most common means of control.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] These handwritten decision trees often result in "artificial stupidity" such as repetitive behavior, loss of immersion, or abnormal behavior in situations the developers did not plan for.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Pathfinding, another common use for AI, is widely seen in real-time strategy games.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Pathfinding is the method for determining how to get a NPC from one point on a map to another, taking into consideration the terrain, obstacles and possibly "fog of war".
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Commercial videogames often use fast and simple "grid-based pathfinding", wherein the terrain is mapped onto a rigid grid of uniform squares and a pathfinding algorithm such as A* or IDA* is applied to the grid.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Instead of just a rigid grid, some games use irregular polygons and assemble a navigation mesh out of the areas of the map that NPCs can walk to.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] As a third method, it is sometimes convenient for developers to manually select "waypoints" that NPCs should use to navigate; the cost is that such waypoints can create unnatural-looking movement.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In addition, waypoints tend to perform worse than navigation meshes in complex environments.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Beyond static pathfinding, navigation is a sub-field of Game AI focusing on giving NPCs the capability to navigate in a dynamic environment, finding a path to a target while avoiding collisions with other entities (other NPC, players...) or collaborating with them (group navigation).
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Navigation in dynamic strategy games with large numbers of units, such as Age of Empires (1997) or Civilization V (2010), often performs poorly; units often get in the way of other units.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Rather than improve the Game AI to properly solve a difficult problem in the virtual environment, it is often more cost-effective to just modify the scenario to be more tractable.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] If pathfinding gets bogged down over a specific obstacle, a developer may just end up moving or deleting the obstacle.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Many contemporary video games fall under the category of action, first-person shooter, or adventure.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In most of these types of games, there is some level of combat that takes place.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The AI's ability to be efficient in combat is important in these genres.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] A common goal today is to make the AI more human or at least appear so.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] One of the more positive and efficient features found in modern-day video game AI is the ability to hunt.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] AI originally reacted in a very black and white manner.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] If the player were in a specific area then the AI would react in either a complete offensive manner or be entirely defensive.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In recent years, the idea of "hunting" has been introduced; in this 'hunting' state the AI will look for realistic markers, such as sounds made by the character or footprints they may have left behind.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] These developments ultimately allow for a more complex form of play.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] With this feature, the player can actually consider how to approach or avoid an enemy.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] This is a feature that is particularly prevalent in the stealth genre.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Another development in recent game AI has been the development of "survival instinct".
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In-game computers can recognize different objects in an environment and determine whether it is beneficial or detrimental to its survival.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Like a user, the AI can look for cover in a firefight before taking actions that would leave it otherwise vulnerable, such as reloading a weapon or throwing a grenade.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] There can be set markers that tell it when to react in a certain way.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] For example, if the AI is given a command to check its health throughout a game then further commands can be set so that it reacts a specific way at a certain percentage of health.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] If the health is below a certain threshold then the AI can be set to run away from the player and avoid it until another function is triggered.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Another example could be if the AI notices it is out of bullets, it will find a cover object and hide behind it until it has reloaded.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Actions like these make the AI seem more human.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] However, there is still a need for improvement in this area.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Another side-effect of combat AI occurs when two AI-controlled characters encounter each other; first popularized in the id Software game *Doom*, so-called 'monster infighting' can break out in certain situations.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Specifically, AI agents that are programmed to respond to hostile attacks will sometimes attack *each other* if their cohort's attacks land too close to them.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In the case of *Doom*, published gameplay manuals even suggest taking advantage of monster infighting in order to survive certain levels and difficulty settings.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Procedural content generation (PCG) is an AI technique to autonomously create ingame content through algorithms with minimal input from designers.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] PCG is typically used to dynamically generate game features such as levels, NPC dialogue, and sounds.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Developers input specific parameters to guide the algorithms into making content for them.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] PCG offers numerous advantages from both a developmental and player experience standpoint.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Game studios are able to spend less money on artists and save time on production.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Players are given a fresh, highly replayable experience as the game generates new content each time they play.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] PCG allows game content to adapt in real time to the player's actions.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Generative algorithms (a rudimentary form of AI) have been used for level creation for decades.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The iconic 1980 dungeon crawler computer game *Rogue* is a foundational example.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Players are tasked with descending through the increasingly difficult levels of a dungeon to retrieve the Amulet of Yendor.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The dungeon levels are algorithmically generated at the start of each game.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The save file is deleted every time the player dies.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The algorithmic dungeon generation creates unique gameplay that would not otherwise be there as the goal of retrieving the amulet is the same each time.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The roguelike video game genre, derived from *Rogue*, feature games that use some type of procedural generation to provide near infinite replayability.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Opinions on total level generation as seen in games like *Rogue* can vary.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Some developers can be skeptical of the quality of generated content and desire to create a world with a more "human" feel so they will use PCG more sparingly.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Consequently, they will only use PCG to generate specific components of an otherwise handcrafted level.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] A notable example of this is Ubisoft's 2017 tactical shooter *Tom Clancy's Ghost Recon Wildlands*.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Developers used a pathfinding algorithm trained with a data set of real maps to create road networks that would weave through handcrafted villages within the game world.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] This is an intelligent use of PCG as the AI would have a large amount of real world data to work with and roads are straightforward to create.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] However, the AI would likely miss nuances and subtleties if it was tasked with creating a village where people live.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] As AI has become more advanced, developer goals are shifting to create massive repositories of levels from data sets.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In 2023, researchers from New York University and the University of the Witwatersrand trained a large language model to generate levels in the style of the 1981 puzzle game *Sokoban*.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] They found that the model excelled at generating levels with specifically requested characteristics such as difficulty level or layout.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] However, current models such as the one used in the study require large datasets of levels to be effective.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] They concluded that, while promising, the high data cost of large language models currently outweighs the benefits for this application.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Continued advancements in the field will likely lead to more mainstream use in the future.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The musical score of a video game is an important expression of the emotional tone of a scene to the player.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Sound effects such as the noise of a weapon hitting an enemy help indicate the effect of the player's actions.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Generating these in real time creates an engaging experience for the player because the game is more responsive to their input.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] An example is the 2013 adventure game *Proteus* where an algorithm dynamically adapts the music based on the angle the player is viewing the ingame landscape from.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Recent breakthroughs in AI have resulted in the creation of advanced tools that are capable of creating music and sound based on evolving factors with minimal developer input.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] One such example is the MetaComposure music generator.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] MetaComposure is an evolutionary algorithm designed to generate original music compositions during real time gameplay to match the current mood of the environment.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The algorithm is able to assess the current mood of the game state through "mood tagging".
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Research indicates that there is a significant positive statistical correlation regarding player rated game engagement and the dynamically generated musical compositions when they accurately match their current emotions.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Generative tools similar to those used in LLMs and diffusion models like Midjourney and DALL-E have been used to generate in-game environments, and companies like Ubisoft have stated that they are experimenting with using AI to generate basic dialogue.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Developers at Roblox are using AI to generate 3D objects for players dubbed Cube 3D, an open-source AI that generates 3D objects based on the methods of LLMs to generate words.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Game AI often amounts to pathfinding and finite-state machines.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Pathfinding gets the AI from point A to point B, usually in the most direct way possible.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] State machines permit transitioning between different behaviors.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The Monte Carlo tree search method provides a more engaging game experience by creating additional obstacles for the player to overcome.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The MCTS consists of a tree diagram in which the AI essentially plays tic-tac-toe.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Depending on the outcome, it selects a pathway yielding the next obstacle for the player.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In complex video games, these trees may have more branches, provided that the player can come up with several strategies to surpass the obstacle.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Academic AI may play a role within game AI, outside the traditional concern of controlling NPC behavior.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Procedural-content generation: Creating elements of the game environment like environmental conditions, levels, and even music in an automated way.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] AI methods can generate new content or interactive stories.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Data mining on user behavior: This allows game designers to explore how people use the game, what parts they play most, and what causes them to stop playing, allowing developers to tune gameplay or improve monetization.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Alternate approaches to NPCs: These include changing the game set-up to enhance NPC believability and exploring social rather than individual NPC behavior.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Rather than procedural generation, some researchers have used generative adversarial networks (GANs) to create new content.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In 2018 researchers at Cornwall University trained a GAN on a thousand human-created levels for *Doom*; following training, the neural net prototype was able to design new playable levels on its own.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Similarly, researchers at the University of California prototyped a GAN to generate levels for Super Mario.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In 2020 Nvidia displayed a GAN-created clone of *Pac-Man*; the GAN learned how to recreate the game by watching 50,000 (mostly bot-generated) playthroughs.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Non-player characters are entities within video games that are not controlled by players, but instead are managed by AI systems.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] NPCs contribute to the immersion, storytelling, and the mechanics of a game.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] They often serve as companions, quest-givers, merchants and much more.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Their realism has advanced significantly in the past few years, thanks to improvements in AI technologies.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] NPCs are essential in both narrative-driven as well as open-world games.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] They help convey the lore and context of the game, making them pivotal to world-building and narrative progression.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] For instance, an NPC can provide critical information, offer quests, or simply populate the world to add a sense of realism to the game.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Additionally, their role as quest-givers or merchants makes them integral to the gameplay loop, giving players access to resources, missions, or services that enable further progression.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Additionally, NPCs can be designed to serve functional roles in games, such as a merchant or to provide a service to the player.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] These characters are central to facilitating game mechanics by acting as intermediaries between the player and in-game systems.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Academics say the interactions between players and NPCs are often designed to be straightforward but contextually relevant, ensuring that the player receives necessary feedback or resources for gameplay continuity.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Recent advancements in artificial intelligence have significantly enhanced the complexity and realism of NPCs.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Before these advancements, AI operated on pre-programmed behaviors, making them predictable and repeatable.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] With AI developing NPCs have become more adaptive and able to dynamically respond to players.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Experts think the integration of deep learning and reinforcement learning techniques has enabled NPCs to adjust their behavior in response to player actions, creating a more interactive and personalized gameplay experience.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] One such development is the use of adaptive behavior models.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] These allow NPCs to analyze and learn from players decisions in real time.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] This behavior allows for a much more engaging experience.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] For example as said by experts in the field, NPCs in modern video games can now react to player actions with increased sophistication, such as adjusting their tactics in combat or changing their dialogue based on past interactions.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] By using deep learning algorithms these systems emulate human-like decisions-making, thus making NPCs feel more like real people rather than static game elements.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Another advancements in NPC AI is the use of natural language processing, which allows NPCs to engage in more realistic conversations with players.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Before this NPC dialogue was limited to a fixed set of responses.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] It is said that NLP has improved the fluidity of NPC conversations, allowing them to respond more contextually to player inputs.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] This development has increased the depth and immersion of player-NPC interactions, as players can now engage in more complex dialogues that affect the storyline and gameplay outcomes.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Additionally, deep learning models have allowed NPCs to become more capable of predicting players behaviors.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Deep learning allows NPCs to process large amounts of data and adapt to player strategies, making interactions with them less predictable and more varied.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] This creates a more immersive experience, as NPCs are now able to "learn" from player behavior, which provides a greater sense of realism within the game.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Recent advancements in AI for video games have led to more complex and adaptive behaviors in non-playable characters (NPCs).
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] For instance, AI systems now utilize sophisticated techniques such as decision trees and state machines to enhance NPC interactions and realism, as discussed in "Artificial Intelligence in Games".
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Recent advancements in AI for video games have also focused on improving dynamic and adaptive behaviors in NPCs.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] For example, recent research has explored the use of complex neural networks to enable NPCs to learn and adapt their behavior based on player actions, enhancing the overall gaming experience.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] This approach is detailed in the IEEE paper on "AI Techniques for Interactive Game Systems".
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Despite all of these advancements in NPC AI, there are still significant challenges that developers face in designing NPCs.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] They need to balance realism, functionally, and players expectations.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The key challenge is to make sure that NPCs enhance the players experience, rather than disturb the gameplay.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Overly realistic NPCs that behave unpredictably can frustrate players by hindering progression or breaking immersion.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Conversely, NPCs that are too predictable or simplistic may fail to engage players, reducing the overall effectiveness of the game's narrative and mechanics.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Another factor that needs to be accounted for is the computation cost of implementing advanced AI for NPCs.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The use of these Advanced AI techniques requires large amount of processing power, which can limit its usage.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Balancing the performance of AI-driven NPCs with the game's overall technical limitations is crucial for ensuring smooth gameplay.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Experts mentioned how developers must allocate resources efficiently to avoid overburdening the game's systems, particularly in large, open-world games where numerous NPCs must interact with the player simultaneously.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Finally, creating NPCs that can respond dynamically to a wide range of player behaviors remains a difficult task.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] NPCs must be able to handle both scripted interactions and unscripted scenarios where players may behave in unexpected ways.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Designing NPCs capable of adapting to such variability requires complex AI models that can account for numerous possible interactions, which can be resource-intensive and time-consuming for developers.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In the context of artificial intelligence in video games, cheating refers to the programmer giving agents actions and access to information that would be unavailable to the player in the same situation.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Believing that the Atari 8-bit could not compete against a human player, Chris Crawford did not fix a bug in *Eastern Front (1941)* that benefited the computer-controlled Russian side.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] *Computer Gaming World* in 1994 reported that "It is a well-known fact that many AIs 'cheat' (or, at least, 'fudge') in order to be able to keep up with human players".
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] For example, if the agents want to know if the player is nearby they can either be given complex, human-like sensors (seeing, hearing, etc.), or they can cheat by simply asking the game engine for the player's position.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Common variations include giving AIs higher speeds in racing games to catch up to the player or spawning them in advantageous positions in first-person shooters.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The use of cheating in AI shows the limitations of the "intelligence" achievable artificially; generally speaking, in games where strategic creativity is important, humans could easily beat the AI after a minimum of trial and error if it were not for this advantage.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Cheating is often implemented for performance reasons where in many cases it may be considered acceptable as long as the effect is not obvious to the player.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] While cheating refers only to privileges given specifically to the AI—it does not include the inhuman swiftness and precision natural to a computer—a player might call the computer's inherent advantages "cheating" if they result in the agent acting unlike a human player.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Sid Meier stated that he omitted multiplayer alliances in *Civilization* because he found that the computer was almost as good as humans in using them, which caused players to think that the computer was cheating.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Developers say that most game AIs are honest but they dislike players erroneously complaining about "cheating" AI.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In addition, humans use tactics against computers that they would not against other people.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In short, cheating AI is when the game seems to break its own rules, producing impossible outcomes.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The opposite is dynamic difficulty, a structured adjustment of AI skill to maintain competition, respecting game mechanics.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Some games may have a blend of both of these systems at once.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In the 1996 game *Creatures*, the user "hatches" small furry animals and teaches them how to behave.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] These "Norns" can talk, feed themselves, and protect themselves against vicious creatures.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] It was the first popular application of machine learning in an interactive simulation.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Neural networks are used by the creatures to learn what to do.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The game is regarded as a breakthrough in artificial life research, which aims to model the behavior of creatures interacting with their environment.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In the 2001 first-person shooter *Halo: Combat Evolved* the player assumes the role of the Master Chief, battling various aliens on foot or in vehicles.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Enemies use cover very wisely, and employ suppressing fire and grenades.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The squad situation affects the individuals, so certain enemies flee when their leader dies.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Attention is paid to the little details, with enemies notably throwing back grenades or team-members responding to being bothered.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The underlying "behavior tree" technology has become very popular in the games industry since *Halo 2*.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The 2005 psychological horror first-person shooter *F.E.A.R.* has player characters engage a battalion of cloned super-soldiers, robots and paranormal creatures.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The AI uses a planner to generate context-sensitive behaviors, the first time in a mainstream game.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] This technology is still used as a reference for many studios.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The Replicas are capable of utilizing the game environment to their advantage, such as overturning tables and shelves to create cover, opening doors, crashing through windows, or even noticing (and alerting the rest of their comrades to) the player's flashlight.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In addition, the AI is also capable of performing flanking maneuvers, using suppressing fire, throwing grenades to flush the player out of cover, and even playing dead.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Most of these actions, in particular the flanking, is the result of emergent behavior.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The survival horror series *S.T.A.L.K.E.R.* (2007–) confronts the player with man-made experiments, military soldiers, and mercenaries known as Stalkers.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The various encountered enemies (if the difficulty level is set to its highest) use combat tactics and behaviors such as healing wounded allies, giving orders, out-flanking the player and using weapons with pinpoint accuracy.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The 2010 real-time strategy game *StarCraft II: Wings of Liberty* gives the player control of one of three factions in a 1v1, 2v2, or 3v3 battle arena.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The player must defeat their opponents by destroying all their units and bases.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] This is accomplished by creating units that are effective at countering opponents' units.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Players can play against multiple different levels of AI difficulty ranging from very easy to Cheater 3 (insane).
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The AI is able to cheat at the difficulty Cheater 1 (vision), where it can see units and bases when a player in the same situation could not.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Cheater 2 gives the AI extra resources, while Cheater 3 gives an extensive advantage over its opponent.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Generative artificial intelligence, AI systems that can respond to prompts and produce text, images, and audio and video clips, arose in 2023 with systems like ChatGPT and Stable Diffusion.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In video games, these systems could create the potential for game assets to be created indefinitely, bypassing typical limitations on human creations.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] For example, the 2024 browser-based sandbox game *Infinite Craft* uses generative AI software, including LLaMA.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] When two elements are being combined, a new element is generated by the AI.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The 2024 browser-based game *Oasis* uses generative AI to simulate the video game *Minecraft*.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] *Oasis* is trained on millions of hours of footage from *Minecraft*, and predicts how the next frame of gameplay looks using this dataset.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] *Oasis* does not have object permanence because it does not store any data.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The 2025 video game *AI2U: With You 'Til The End*, developed by AlterStaff Inc., used ChatGPT for the non-playable characters dialogue in the game.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Generative artificial intelligence has been included to perform video upscaling of game images.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Both NVidia's Deep Learning Super Sampling (DLSS) and AMD's FidelityFX Super Resolution (FSR) have included AI as part of their engine.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In March 2026, NVidia announced version 5.0 of DLSS to release later in 2026, which among other improvements, includes an AI engine that "infuses pixels with photoreal lighting and materials" as to make existing game graphics appear more realistic.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] NVidia's Jensen Huang said that developers will far more control over how DLSS 5.0 would interact with their games, allowing the developer to tweak lighting and texture adjustments, and that NVidia was continuing to improve the technology before its release.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] However, there are similar concerns in other fields particularly the potential for loss of jobs normally dedicated to the creation of these assets.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Voice actors were one of the first groups to express concern on generative AI use in video games.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The North American actor's union SAG-AFTRA had finished a strike in 2023 against television and film production companies, with the strike concluded on new contract terms that gave actors strong control over whether their voices could be used to train generative AI engines.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Shortly afterward, the union agreed to a contract with AI company Replica Studios to allow union voices to be used to train AI and used in games, with the contract assuring pay and rights protections.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] While the contract was agreed upon by a SAG-AFTRA committee, many members expressed criticism of the move, having not been told of it until it was completed and that the deal did not do enough to protect the actors.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The strike concluded by July 2025 with the affected publishers agreeing to a contract that gave actors stronger control of whether their voices could be used for AI.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] To assure such content was disclosed by game publishers and avoid potential copyright issues, Valve implemented new requirements for games on Steam that the use of pre-generated AI assets or live generation via generative AI must be disclosed on the storefront page.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Sweeney criticized this move, as "it makes it much, much, much harder for a game developer to have a chance of success.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] *Deterministic* refers to the uniqueness of the computation run.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] In search of the simplest models to capture finite-state machines, Warren McCulloch and Walter Pitts were among the first researchers to introduce a concept similar to finite automata in 1943.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] The figure illustrates a deterministic finite automaton using a state diagram.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] In this example automaton, there are three states: S0, S1, and S2 (denoted graphically by circles).
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] The automaton takes a finite sequence of 0s and 1s as input.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] For each state, there is a transition arrow leading out to a next state for both 0 and 1.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] Upon reading a symbol, a DFA jumps *deterministically* from one state to another by following the transition arrow.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] For example, if the automaton is currently in state S0 and the current input symbol is 1, then it deterministically jumps to state S1.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] A DFA has a *start state* (denoted graphically by an arrow coming in from nowhere) where computations begin, and a set of *accept states* (denoted graphically by a double circle) which help define when a computation is successful.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] A DFA is defined as an abstract mathematical concept, but is often implemented in hardware and software for solving various specific problems such as lexical analysis and pattern matching.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] For example, a DFA can model software that decides whether or not online user input such as email addresses are syntactically valid.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] DFAs have been generalized to *nondeterministic finite automata (NFA)* which may have several arrows of the same label starting from a state.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] Using the powerset construction method, every NFA can be translated to a DFA that recognizes the same language.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] DFAs, and NFAs as well, recognize exactly the set of regular languages.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] Let *w* = *a*1*a*2...*an* be a string over the alphabet Σ.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] In words, the first condition says that the machine starts in the start state *q*0.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] The second condition says that given each character of string w, the machine will transition from state to state according to the transition function δ.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] The last condition says that the machine accepts w if the last input of w causes the machine to halt in one of the accepting states.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] Otherwise, it is said that the automaton *rejects* the string.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] The set of strings that M accepts is the language *recognized* by M and this language is denoted by *L*(*M*).
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] A deterministic finite automaton without accept states and without a starting state is known as a transition system or semiautomaton.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] For more comprehensive introduction of the formal definition see automata theory.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] The following example is of a DFA M, with a binary alphabet, which requires that the input contains an even number of 0s.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] The state *S*1 represents that there has been an even number of 0s in the input so far, while *S*2 signifies an odd number.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] A 1 in the input does not change the state of the automaton.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] When the input ends, the state will show whether the input contained an even number of 0s or not.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] If the input did contain an even number of 0s, M will finish in state *S*1, an accepting state, so the input string will be accepted.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] The language recognized by M is the regular language given by the regular expression `(1*) (0 (1*) 0 (1*))*`, where `*` is the Kleene star, e.g., `1*` denotes any number (possibly zero) of consecutive ones.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] According to the above definition, deterministic finite automata are always *complete*: they define from each state a transition for each input symbol.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] While this is the most common definition, some authors use the term deterministic finite automaton for a slightly different notion: an automaton that defines *at most* one transition for each state and each input symbol; the transition function is allowed to be partial.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] When no transition is defined, such an automaton halts.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] A **local automaton** is a DFA, not necessarily complete, for which all edges with the same label lead to a single vertex.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] Local automata accept the class of local languages, those for which membership of a word in the language is determined by a "sliding window" of length two on the word.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] A **Myhill graph** over an alphabet *A* is a directed graph with vertex set *A* and subsets of vertices labelled "start" and "finish".
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] The language accepted by a Myhill graph is the set of directed paths from a start vertex to a finish vertex: the graph thus acts as an automaton.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] The class of languages accepted by Myhill graphs is the class of local languages.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] When the start state and accept states are ignored, a DFA of n states and an alphabet of size k can be seen as a digraph of n vertices in which all vertices have k out-arcs labeled 1, ..., *k* (a k-out digraph).
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] It is known that when *k* ≥ 2 is a fixed integer, with high probability, the largest strongly connected component (SCC) in such a k-out digraph chosen uniformly at random is of linear size and it can be reached by all vertices.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] It has also been proven that if k is allowed to increase as n increases, then the whole digraph has a phase transition for strong connectivity similar to Erdős–Rényi model for connectivity.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] In a random DFA, the maximum number of vertices reachable from one vertex is very close to the number of vertices in the largest SCC with high probability.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] This is also true for the largest induced sub-digraph of minimum in-degree one, which can be seen as a directed version of 1-core.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] If DFAs recognize the languages that are obtained by applying an operation on the DFA recognizable languages then DFAs are said to be closed under the operation.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] The DFAs are closed under the following operations.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] For each operation, an optimal construction with respect to the number of states has been determined in state complexity research.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] Since DFAs are equivalent to nondeterministic finite automata (NFA), these closures may also be proved using closure properties of NFA.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] A run of a given DFA can be seen as a sequence of compositions of a very general formulation of the transition function with itself.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] For a given input symbol $a\in \Sigma$ , one may construct a transition function $\delta _{a}:Q\rightarrow Q$ by defining $\delta _{a}(q)=\delta (q,a)$ for all $q\in Q$ .
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] (This trick is called currying.) From this perspective, $\delta _{a}$ "acts" on a state in Q to yield another state.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] One may then consider the result of function composition repeatedly applied to the various functions $\delta _{a}$ , $\delta _{b}$ , and so on.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] Given a pair of letters $a,b\in \Sigma$ , one may define a new function ${\widehat {\delta }}_{ab}=\delta _{a}\circ \delta _{b}$ , where $\circ$ denotes function composition.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] ${\widehat {\delta }}$ is defined for all words $w\in \Sigma ^{*}$ .
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] A run of the DFA is a sequence of compositions of ${\widehat {\delta }}$ with itself.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] Repeated function composition forms a monoid.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] For the transition functions, this monoid is known as the transition monoid, or sometimes the *transformation semigroup*.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] The construction can also be reversed: given a ${\widehat {\delta }}$ , one can reconstruct a $\delta$ , and so the two descriptions are equivalent.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] DFAs are one of the most practical models of computation, since there is a trivial linear time, constant-space, online algorithm to simulate a DFA on a stream of input.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] DFAs are equivalent in computing power to nondeterministic finite automata (NFAs).
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] This is because, firstly any DFA is also an NFA, so an NFA can do what a DFA can do.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] Also, given an NFA, using the powerset construction one can build a DFA that recognizes the same language as the NFA, although the DFA could have exponentially larger number of states than the NFA.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] However, even though NFAs are computationally equivalent to DFAs, the above-mentioned problems are not necessarily solved efficiently also for NFAs.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] The non-universality problem for NFAs is PSPACE complete since there are small NFAs with shortest rejecting word in exponential size.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] A DFA is universal if and only if all states are final states, but this does not hold for NFAs.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] The Equality, Inclusion and Minimization Problems are also PSPACE complete since they require forming the complement of an NFA which results in an exponential blow up of size.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] On the other hand, finite-state automata are of strictly limited power in the languages they can recognize; many simple languages, including any problem that requires more than constant space to solve, cannot be recognized by a DFA.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] The classic example of a simply described language that no DFA can recognize is bracket or Dyck language, i.e., the language that consists of properly paired brackets such as word "(()())".
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] Intuitively, no DFA can recognize the Dyck language because DFAs are not capable of counting: a DFA-like automaton needs to have a state to represent any possible number of "currently open" parentheses, meaning it would need an unbounded number of states.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] Another simpler example is the language consisting of strings of the form *anbn* for some finite but arbitrary number of *a*'s, followed by an equal number of *b*'s.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] Given a set of *positive* words $S^{+}\subset \Sigma ^{*}$ and a set of *negative* words $S^{-}\subset \Sigma ^{*}$ one can construct a DFA that accepts all words from $S^{+}$ and rejects all words from $S^{-}$ : this problem is called *DFA identification* (synthesis, learning).
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] While *some* DFA can be constructed in linear time, the problem of identifying a DFA with the minimal number of states is NP-complete.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] The first algorithm for minimal DFA identification has been proposed by Trakhtenbrot and Barzdin and is called the *TB-algorithm*.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] However, the TB-algorithm assumes that all words from $\Sigma$ up to a given length are contained in either $S^{+}\cup S^{-}$ .
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] Lang proposed an extension of the TB-algorithm that does not use any assumptions about $S^{+}$ and $S^{-}$ , the *Traxbar* algorithm.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] However, Traxbar does not guarantee the minimality of the constructed DFA.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] Gold also proposed a heuristic algorithm for minimal DFA identification.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] Gold's algorithm assumes that $S^{+}$ and $S^{-}$ contain a *characteristic set* of the regular language; otherwise, the constructed DFA will be inconsistent either with $S^{+}$ or $S^{-}$ .
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] Other notable DFA identification algorithms include the RPNI algorithm, the Blue-Fringe evidence-driven state-merging algorithm, and Windowed-EDSM.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] Yet another step forward is due to application of SAT solvers by Marjin J.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] Verwer: the minimal DFA identification problem is reduced to deciding the satisfiability of a Boolean formula.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] Though this approach allows finding the minimal DFA, it suffers from exponential blow-up of execution time when the size of input data increases.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] Therefore, Heule and Verwer's initial algorithm has later been augmented with making several steps of the EDSM algorithm prior to SAT solver execution: the DFASAT algorithm.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] This allows reducing the search space of the problem, but leads to loss of the minimality guarantee.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] Another way of reducing the search space has been proposed by Ulyantsev et al. by means of new symmetry breaking predicates based on the breadth-first search algorithm: the sought DFA's states are constrained to be numbered according to the BFS algorithm launched from the initial state.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] This approach reduces the search space by $C!$ by eliminating isomorphic automata.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] The machine always accepts a regular language.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/deterministic-finite-automaton] There must exist at least one element of the set F (a **HALT** state) for the language to be nonempty.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] In theoretical computer science, a **finite-state machine** (**FSM**) or **finite-state automaton** (**FSA**, plural: *automata*), **finite automaton**, or simply a **state machine**, is a mathematical model of computation.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] It is an abstract machine that can be in exactly one of a finite number of *states* at any given time.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] The FSM can change from one state to another in response to some inputs; the change from one state to another is called a *transition*.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] An FSM is defined by a list of its states, its initial state, and the inputs that trigger each transition.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] Finite-state machines are of two types—deterministic finite-state machines and non-deterministic finite-state machines.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] For any non-deterministic finite-state machine, an equivalent deterministic one can be constructed.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] The behavior of state machines can be observed in many devices in modern society that perform a predetermined sequence of actions depending on a sequence of events with which they are presented.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] The finite-state machine has less computational power than some other models of computation such as the Turing machine.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] The computational power distinction means there are computational tasks that a Turing machine can do but an FSM cannot.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] This is because an FSM's memory is limited by the number of states it has.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] A finite-state machine has the same computational power as a Turing machine that is restricted such that its head may only perform "read" operations, and always has to move from left to right.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] FSMs are studied in the more general field of automata theory.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] An example of a simple mechanism that can be modeled by a state machine is a turnstile.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] A turnstile, used to control access to subways and amusement park rides, is a gate with three rotating arms at waist height, one across the entryway.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] Initially the arms are locked, blocking the entry, preventing patrons from passing through.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] Depositing a coin or token in a slot on the turnstile unlocks the arms, allowing a single customer to push through.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] After the customer passes through, the arms are locked again until another coin is inserted.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] Considered as a state machine, the turnstile has two possible states: *Locked* and *Unlocked*.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] There are two possible inputs that affect its state: putting a coin in the slot (*coin*) and pushing the arm (*push*).
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] In the locked state, pushing on the arm has no effect; no matter how many times the input *push* is given, it stays in the locked state.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] Putting a coin in – that is, giving the machine a *coin* input – shifts the state from *Locked* to *Unlocked*.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] In the unlocked state, putting additional coins in has no effect; that is, giving additional *coin* inputs does not change the state.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] A customer pushing through the arms gives a *push* input and resets the state to *Locked*.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] The turnstile state machine can also be represented by a directed graph called a state diagram *(above)*.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] Each state is represented by a node (*circle*).
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] Edges (*arrows*) show the transitions from one state to another.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] Each arrow is labeled with the input that triggers that transition.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] An input that doesn't cause a change of state (such as a *coin* input in the *Unlocked* state) is represented by a circular arrow returning to the original state.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] The arrow into the *Locked* node from the black dot indicates it is the initial state.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] A *state* is a description of the status of a system that is waiting to execute a *transition*.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] A transition is a set of actions to be executed when a condition is fulfilled or when an event is received.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] For example, when using an audio system to listen to the radio (the system is in the "radio" state), receiving a "next" stimulus results in moving to the next station.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] When the system is in the "CD" state, the "next" stimulus results in moving to the next track.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] Identical stimuli trigger different actions depending on the current state.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] Several state-transition table types are used.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] The most common representation is shown below: the combination of current state (e.g.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] By itself, the table cannot completely describe the action, so it is common to use footnotes.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] Other related representations may not have this limitation.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] For example, an FSM definition including the full action's information is possible using state tables (see also virtual finite-state machine).
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] The Unified Modeling Language has a notation for describing state machines.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] UML state machines overcome the limitations of traditional finite-state machines while retaining their main benefits.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] UML state machines introduce the new concepts of hierarchically nested states and orthogonal regions, while extending the notion of actions.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] UML state machines have the characteristics of both Mealy machines and Moore machines.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] They support actions that depend on both the state of the system and the triggering event, as in Mealy machines, as well as entry and exit actions, which are associated with states rather than transitions, as in Moore machines.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] SDL embeds basic data types called "Abstract Data Types", an action language, and an execution semantic in order to make the finite-state machine executable.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] There are a large number of variants to represent an FSM such as the one in figure 3.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] In addition to their use in modeling reactive systems presented here, finite-state machines are significant in many different areas, including electrical engineering, linguistics, computer science, philosophy, biology, mathematics, video game programming, and logic.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] Finite-state machines are a class of automata studied in automata theory and the theory of computation.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] In computer science, finite-state machines are widely used in modeling of application behavior (control theory), design of hardware digital systems, software engineering, compilers, network protocols, and computational linguistics.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] Finite-state machines can be subdivided into acceptors, classifiers, transducers and sequencers.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] A (possibly infinite) set of symbol sequences, called a formal language, is a regular language if there is some acceptor that accepts *exactly* that set.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] For example, the set of binary strings with an even number of zeroes is a regular language (cf.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] 5), while the set of all strings whose length is a prime number is not.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] An acceptor could also be described as defining a language that would contain every string accepted by the acceptor but none of the rejected ones; that language is *accepted* by the acceptor.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] By definition, the languages accepted by acceptors are the regular languages.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] The problem of determining the language accepted by a given acceptor is an instance of the algebraic path problem—itself a generalization of the shortest path problem to graphs with edges weighted by the elements of an (arbitrary) semiring.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] An example of an accepting state appears in Fig.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] 5: a deterministic finite automaton (DFA) that detects whether the binary input string contains an even number of 0s.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] The FSM uses only entry actions, i.e., output depends only on state.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] The advantage of the Moore model is a simplification of the behaviour.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] The state machine recognizes two commands: "command_open" and "command_close", which trigger state changes.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] The entry action (E:) in state "Opening" starts a motor opening the door, the entry action in state "Closing" starts a motor in the other direction closing the door.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] States "Opened" and "Closed" stop the motor when fully opened or closed.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] They signal to the outside world (e.g., to other state machines) the situation: "door is open" or "door is closed".
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] The FSM also uses input actions, i.e., output depends on input and state.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] The use of a Mealy FSM leads often to a reduction of the number of states.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] There are two input actions (I:): "start motor to close the door if command_close arrives" and "start motor in the other direction to open the door if command_open arrives".
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] The "opening" and "closing" intermediate states are not shown.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] A further distinction is between *deterministic* (DFA) and *non-deterministic* (NFA, GNFA) automata.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] In a deterministic automaton, every state has exactly one transition for each possible input.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] In a non-deterministic automaton, an input can lead to one, more than one, or no transition for a given state.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] The powerset construction algorithm can transform any nondeterministic automaton into a (usually more complex) deterministic automaton with identical functionality.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] A finite-state machine with only one state is called a "combinatorial FSM".
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] It only allows actions upon transition *into* a state.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] This concept is useful in cases where a number of finite-state machines are required to work together, and when it is convenient to consider a purely combinatorial part as a form of FSM to suit the design tools.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] There are other sets of semantics available to represent state machines.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] For example, there are tools for modeling and designing logic for embedded controllers.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] They combine hierarchical state machines (which usually have more than one current state), flow graphs, and truth tables into one language, resulting in a different formalism and set of semantics.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] These charts, like Harel's original state machines, support hierarchically nested states, orthogonal regions, state actions, and transition actions.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] In accordance with the general classification, the following formal definitions are found.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] For both deterministic and non-deterministic FSMs, it is conventional to allow $\delta$ to be a partial function, i.e. $\delta (s,x)$ does not have to be defined for every combination of $s\in S$ and $x\in \Sigma$ .
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] If an FSM M is in a state s , the next symbol is x and $\delta (s,x)$ is not defined, then M can announce an error (i.e. reject the input).
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] This is useful in definitions of general state machines, but less useful when transforming the machine.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] Some algorithms in their default form may require total functions.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] That is, each formal language accepted by a finite-state machine is accepted by such a kind of restricted Turing machine, and vice versa.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] If the output function depends on the state and input symbol ( $\omega :S\times \Sigma \rightarrow \Gamma$ ) that definition corresponds to the *Mealy model*, and can be modelled as a Mealy machine.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] If the output function depends only on the state ( $\omega :S\rightarrow \Gamma$ ) that definition corresponds to the *Moore model*, and can be modelled as a Moore machine.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] A finite-state machine with no output function at all is known as a semiautomaton or transition system.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] If we disregard the first output symbol of a Moore machine, $\omega (s_{0})$ , then it can be readily converted to an output-equivalent Mealy machine by setting the output function of every Mealy transition (i.e. labeling every edge) with the output symbol given of the destination Moore state.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] The converse transformation is less straightforward because a Mealy machine state may have different output labels on its incoming transitions (edges).
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] Every such state needs to be split in multiple Moore machine states, one for every incident output symbol.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] Optimizing an FSM means finding a machine with the minimum number of states that performs the same function.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] The fastest known algorithm doing this is the Hopcroft minimization algorithm.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] Other techniques include using an implication table, or the Moore reduction procedure.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] Additionally, acyclic FSAs can be minimized in linear time.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] In a digital circuit, an FSM may be built using a programmable logic device, a programmable logic controller, logic gates and flip flops or relays.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] More specifically, a hardware implementation requires a register to store state variables, a block of combinational logic that determines the state transition, and a second block of combinational logic that determines the output of an FSM.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] In a *Medvedev machine*, the output is directly connected to the state flip-flops minimizing the time delay between flip-flops and output.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] Through state encoding for low power state machines may be optimized to minimize power consumption.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] Finite automata are often used in the frontend of programming language compilers.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] Such a frontend may comprise several finite-state machines that implement a lexical analyzer and a parser.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] Starting from a sequence of characters, the lexical analyzer builds a sequence of language tokens (such as reserved words, literals, and identifiers) from which the parser builds a syntax tree.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/finite-state-machine] The lexical analyzer and the parser handle the regular and context-free parts of the programming language's grammar.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/non-player-character] A **non-player character** (**NPC**) is a character in a game that is not controlled by a player.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/non-player-character] The term originated in traditional tabletop role-playing games where it applies to characters controlled by the gamemaster, or referee, rather than by another player.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/non-player-character] In video games, this term usually means a computer-controlled character that has a predetermined set of behaviors that potentially will impact gameplay.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/non-player-character] In traditional tabletop role-playing games (RPG) such as *Dungeons & Dragons*, an NPC is a character portrayed by a gamemaster (GM).
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/non-player-character] While the player characters (PCs) form the narrative's protagonists, non-player characters can be thought of as the "supporting cast" or "extras" of a roleplaying narrative.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/non-player-character] Non-player characters populate the fictional world of the game, and can fill any role not occupied by a player character.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/non-player-character] Non-player characters might be allies, bystanders, or competitors to the PCs.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/non-player-character] NPCs can also be traders who trade currency for things such as equipment or gear.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/non-player-character] NPCs thus vary in their level of detail.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/non-player-character] Some may be only a brief description ("You see a man in a corner of the tavern"), while others may have complete game statistics and backstories.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/non-player-character] There is some debate about how much work a gamemaster should put into an important NPC's statistics; some players prefer to have every NPC completely defined with stats, skills, and gear, while others define only what is immediately necessary and fill in the rest as the game proceeds.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/non-player-character] There is also some debate regarding the importance of fully defined NPCs in any given role-playing game, but there is consensus that the more "real" the NPCs feel, the more fun players will have interacting with them in character.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/non-player-character] Many game systems have rules for characters sustaining positive allies in the form of NPC followers, hired hands, or other dependents stature to the PC (player character).
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/non-player-character] Characters may sometimes help in the design, recruitment, or development of NPCs.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/non-player-character] In the *Champions* game (and related games using the Hero System), a character may have a DNPC, or "dependent non-player character".
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/non-player-character] This is a character controlled by the GM, but for which the player character is responsible in some way, and who may be put in harm's way by the PC's choices.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/non-player-character] The term "non-player character" is also used in video games to describe entities not under the direct control of a player.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/non-player-character] The term carries a connotation that the character is not hostile towards players; hostile characters are referred to as enemies, mobs, or creeps.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/non-player-character] NPC behavior in computer games is usually scripted and automatic, triggered by certain actions or dialogue with the player characters.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/non-player-character] In certain multiplayer games (*Neverwinter Nights* and *Vampire: The Masquerade* series, for example) a player that acts as the GM can "possess" both player and non-player characters, controlling their actions to further the storyline.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/non-player-character] More complex games, such as the aforementioned *Neverwinter Nights*, allow the player to customize the NPCs' behavior by modifying their default scripts or creating entirely new ones.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/non-player-character] In some online games, such as massively multiplayer online role-playing games, NPCs may be entirely unscripted, and are essentially regular character avatars controlled by employees of the game company.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/non-player-character] These "non-players" are often distinguished from player characters by avatar appearance or other visual designation, and often serve as in-game support for new players.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/non-player-character] In other cases, these "live" NPCs are virtual actors, playing regular characters that drive a continuing storyline (as in *Myst Online: Uru Live*).
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/non-player-character] In earlier RPGs, NPCs only had monologues.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/non-player-character] This is typically represented by a dialogue box, floating text, cutscene, or other means of displaying the NPCs' speech or reaction to the player.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/non-player-character] NPC speeches of this kind are often designed to give an instant impression of the character of the speaker, providing character vignettes, but they may also advance the story or illuminate the world around the PC.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/non-player-character] Similar to this is the most common form of storytelling, non-branching dialogue, in which the means of displaying NPC speech are the same as above, but the player character or avatar responds to or initiates speech with NPCs.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/non-player-character] In addition to the purposes listed above, this enables the development of the player character.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/non-player-character] More advanced RPGs feature interactive dialogue, or branching dialogue (dialogue trees).
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/non-player-character] An example are the games produced by Black Isle Studios and White Wolf, Inc.; every one of their games is multiple-choice roleplaying.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/non-player-character] When talking to an NPC, the player is presented with a list of dialogue options and may choose between them.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/non-player-character] Each choice may result in a different response from the NPC.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/non-player-character] These choices may affect the course of the game, as well as the conversation.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/non-player-character] At the least, they provide a reference point to the player of their character's relationship with the game world.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/non-player-character] These games often feature a day-night cycle with a time scheduling system that provides context and relevance to character interactions, allowing players to choose when and if to interact with certain characters, which in turn influences their responses during later conversations.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/non-player-character] In 2023, Replica Studios unveiled its AI-developed NPCs for the *Unreal Engine 5*, in cooperation with OpenAI, which enable players to have an interactive conversation with unplayable characters.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/non-player-character] "NPC streaming"—livestreaming while mimicking the behaviors of an NPC—became popular on TikTok in 2023 and was largely popularized by livestreamer Pinkydoll.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/non-player-character] From around 2018, the term NPC became an insult, primarily online, to suggest that a person is unable to form thoughts or opinions of their own.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/non-player-character] This is sometimes illustrated with a grey-faced, expressionless version of the Wojak meme.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/non-player-character] NPC streaming is a type of livestream that allows users to participate in and shape the content they are viewing in real time.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/non-player-character] It has become widely popular as influencers and users of social media platforms such as TikTok utilize livestreams to act as non-player characters.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/non-player-character] "Viewers in NPC live streams take on the role of puppeteers, influencing the creator's next move." This phenomenon has been on the rise as viewers are actively involved in what they are watching, by purchasing digital "gifts" and sending them directly to the streamer.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/non-player-character] In return, the streamer will briefly mimic a character or act.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/non-player-character] This phenomenon has become a trend starting from July 2023, as influencers make profits from this new internet character.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/non-player-character] Pinkydoll, a TikTok influencer, gained 400,000 followers the same month that she started NPC streaming, while her livestreams began to earn her as much as $7,000 in a day.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/non-player-character] NPC streaming gives creators a new avenue to earn money online.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/non-player-character] Despite this, certain creators are quitting due to certain stigmas that come with the strategy.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/non-player-character] For example, a pioneer of the NPC trend, Malik Ambersley has been robbed, accosted by police, and gotten into fights due to the controversial nature of his act.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/state-pattern] The **state pattern** is a behavioral software design pattern that allows an object to alter its behavior when its internal state changes.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/state-pattern] This pattern is close to the concept of finite-state machines.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/state-pattern] The state pattern can be interpreted as a strategy pattern, which is able to switch a strategy through invocations of methods defined in the pattern's interface.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/state-pattern] The state pattern is used in computer programming to encapsulate varying behavior for the same object, based on its internal state.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/state-pattern] This can be a cleaner way for an object to change its behavior at runtime without resorting to conditional statements and thus improve maintainability.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/state-pattern] The state design pattern is one of twenty-three design patterns documented by the Gang of Four that describe how to solve recurring design problems.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/state-pattern] Such problems cover the design of flexible and reusable object-oriented software, such as objects that are easy to implement, change, test, and reuse.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/state-pattern] Implementing state-specific behavior directly within a class is inflexible because it commits the class to a particular behavior and makes it impossible to add a new state or change the behavior of an existing state later, independently from the class, without changing the class.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/state-pattern] This makes a class independent of how state-specific behavior is implemented.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/state-pattern] New states can be added by defining new state classes.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/state-pattern] A class can change its behavior at run-time by changing its current state object.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/state-pattern] In the accompanying Unified Modeling Language (UML) class diagram, the `Context` class doesn't implement state-specific behavior directly.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/state-pattern] Instead, `Context` refers to the `State` interface for performing state-specific behavior (`state.handle()`), which makes `Context` independent of how state-specific behavior is implemented.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/state-pattern] The `ConcreteStateA` and `ConcreteStateB` classes implement the `State` interface, that is, implement (encapsulate) the state-specific behavior for each state.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/state-pattern] The `Context` object delegates state-specific behavior to different `State` objects.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/state-pattern] First, `Context` calls `handle(this)` on its current (initial) state object (`ConcreteStateA`), which performs the operation and calls `setState(ConcreteStateB)` on `Context` to change context's current state to `ConcreteStateB`.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/state-pattern] The next time, `Context` again calls `handle(this)` on its current state object (`ConcreteStateB`), which performs the operation and changes context's current state to `ConcreteStateA`.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/state-pattern] This is a C++ example demonstrating the state pattern.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] UML state machine is an object-based variant of Harel statechart, adapted and extended by UML.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] The goal of UML state machines is to overcome the main limitations of traditional finite-state machines while retaining their main benefits.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] UML statecharts introduce the new concepts of hierarchically nested states and orthogonal regions, while extending the notion of actions.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] The term "UML state machine" can refer to two kinds of state machines: *behavioral state machines* and *protocol state machines*.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Behavioral state machines can be used to model the behavior of individual entities (e.g., class instances), a subsystem, a package, or even an entire system.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Protocol state machines are used to express usage protocols and can be used to specify the legal usage scenarios of classifiers, interfaces, and ports.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Many software systems are event-driven, which means that they continuously wait for the occurrence of some external or internal **event** such as a mouse click, a button press, a time tick, or an arrival of a data packet.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] After recognizing the event, such systems react by performing the appropriate computation that may include manipulating the hardware or generating “soft” events that trigger other internal software components.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] (That's why event-driven systems are alternatively called **reactive systems**.) Once the event handling is complete, the system goes back to waiting for the next event.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] The response to an event generally depends on both the type of the event and on the internal **state** of the system and can include a change of state leading to a **state transition**.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] The pattern of events, states, and state transitions among those states can be abstracted and represented as a **finite-state machine** (FSM).
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] The concept of a FSM is important in event-driven programming because it makes the event handling explicitly dependent on both the event-type and on the state of the system.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] When used correctly, a state machine can drastically cut down the number of execution paths through the code, simplify the conditions tested at each branching point, and simplify the switching between different modes of execution.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Conversely, using event-driven programming without an underlying FSM model can lead programmers to produce error prone, difficult to extend and excessively complex application code.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] UML preserves the general form of the traditional state diagrams.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] The UML state diagrams are directed graphs in which nodes denote states and connectors denote state transitions.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] For example, Figure 1 shows a UML state diagram corresponding to the computer keyboard state machine.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] In UML, states are represented as rounded rectangles labeled with state names.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] The transitions, represented as arrows, are labeled with the triggering events followed optionally by the list of executed actions.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] The **initial transition** originates from the solid circle and specifies the default state when the system first begins.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Every state diagram should have such a transition, which should not be labeled, since it is not triggered by an event.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] The initial transition can have associated actions.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] An **event** is something that happens that affects the system.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Strictly speaking, in the UML specification, the term event refers to the type of occurrence rather than to any concrete instance of that occurrence.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] For example, Keystroke is an event for the keyboard, but each press of a key is not an event but a concrete instance of the Keystroke event.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Another event of interest for the keyboard might be Power-on, but turning the power on tomorrow at 10:05:36 will be just an instance of the Power-on event.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] An event can have associated **parameters**, allowing the event instance to convey not only the occurrence of some interesting incident but also quantitative information regarding that occurrence.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] For example, the Keystroke event generated by pressing a key on a computer keyboard has associated parameters that convey the character scan code as well as the status of the Shift, Ctrl, and Alt keys.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] An event instance outlives the instantaneous occurrence that generated it and might convey this occurrence to one or more state machines.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Once generated, the event instance goes through a processing life cycle that can consist of up to three stages.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] First, the event instance is **received** when it is accepted and waiting for processing (e.g., it is placed on the event queue).
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Later, the event instance is **dispatched** to the state machine, at which point it becomes the current event.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Finally, it is **consumed** when the state machine finishes processing the event instance.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] A consumed event instance is no longer available for processing.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Each state machine has a **state**, which governs reaction of the state machine to events.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] For example, when you strike a key on a keyboard, the character code generated will be either an uppercase or a lowercase character, depending on whether the Caps Lock is active.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Therefore, the keyboard's behavior can be divided into two states: the "default" state and the "caps_locked" state.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] A state can abstract away all possible (but irrelevant) event sequences and capture only the relevant ones.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] The idea of *state variable* (and classical FSM model) is that the value of the *state variable* fully defines the current state of the system at any given time.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] The concept of the state reduces the problem of identifying the execution context in the code to testing just the state variable instead of many variables, thus eliminating a lot of conditional logic.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] In practice, however, interpreting the whole state of the state machine as a single *state variable* quickly becomes impractical for all state machines beyond very simple ones.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Indeed, even if we have a single 32-bit integer in our machine state, it could contribute to over 4 billion different states - and will lead to a premature *state explosion*.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] This interpretation is not practical, so in UML state machines the whole *state* of the state machine is commonly split into (a) an enumerable *state variable* and (b) all the other variables which are named *extended state*.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Another way to see it is to interpret the enumerable *state variable* as a qualitative aspect and the *extended state* as quantitative aspects of the whole state.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] In this interpretation, a change of variable does not always imply a change of the qualitative aspects of the system behavior and therefore does not lead to a change of state.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] State machines supplemented with *extended state* variables are called **extended state machines** and UML state machines belong to this category.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Extended state machines can apply the underlying formalism to much more complex problems than is practical without including extended state variables.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] The state diagram from Figure 2 is an example of an extended state machine, in which the complete condition of the system (called the *extended state*) is the combination of a qualitative aspect—the *state variable*—and the quantitative aspects—the *extended state* variables.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] The obvious advantage of extended state machines is flexibility.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] For example, changing the limit governed by `key_count` from 1000 to 10000 keystrokes, would not complicate the extended state machine at all.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] The only modification required would be changing the initialization value of the `key_count` extended state variable during initialization.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] This flexibility of extended state machines comes with a price, however, because of the complex coupling between the "qualitative" and the "quantitative" aspects of the extended state.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] The coupling occurs through the guard conditions attached to transitions, as shown in Figure 2.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] The need for guards is the immediate consequence of adding memory extended state variables to the state machine formalism.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Used sparingly, extended state variables and guards make up a powerful mechanism that can simplify designs.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] On the other hand, it is possible to abuse extended states and guards quite easily.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] When an event instance is dispatched, the state machine responds by performing **actions**, such as changing a variable, performing I/O, invoking a function, generating another event instance, or changing to another state.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Any parameter values associated with the current event are available to all actions directly caused by that event.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Switching from one state to another is called **state transition**, and the event that causes it is called the triggering event, or simply the **trigger**.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] In the keyboard example, if the keyboard is in the "default" state when the CapsLock key is pressed, the keyboard will enter the "caps_locked" state.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] However, if the keyboard is already in the "caps_locked" state, pressing CapsLock will cause a different transition—from the "caps_locked" to the "default" state.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] In both cases, pressing CapsLock is the triggering event.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] In extended state machines, a transition can have a guard, which means that the transition can "fire" only if the guard evaluates to TRUE.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] A state can have many transitions in response to the same trigger, as long as they have nonoverlapping guards; however, this situation could create problems in the sequence of evaluation of the guards when the common trigger occurs.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] The UML specification intentionally does not stipulate any particular order; rather, UML puts the burden on the designer to devise guards in such a way that the order of their evaluation does not matter.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Practically, this means that guard expressions should have no side effects, at least none that would alter evaluation of other guards having the same trigger.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] All state machine formalisms, including UML state machines, universally assume that a state machine completes processing of each event before it can start processing the next event.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] This model of execution is called *run to completion*, or RTC.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] In the RTC model, the system processes events in discrete, indivisible RTC steps.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] New incoming events cannot interrupt the processing of the current event and must be stored (typically in an event queue) until the state machine becomes idle again.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] These semantics completely avoid any internal concurrency issues within a single state machine.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] The RTC model also gets around the conceptual problem of processing actions associated with transitions, where the state machine is not in a well-defined state (is between two states) for the duration of the action.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] During event processing, the system is unresponsive (unobservable), so the ill-defined state during that time has no practical significance.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Note, however, that RTC does not mean that a state machine has to monopolize the CPU until the RTC step is complete.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] The preemption restriction only applies to the task context of the state machine that is already busy processing events.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] In a multitasking environment, other tasks (not related to the task context of the busy state machine) can be running, possibly preempting the currently executing state machine.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] As long as other state machines do not share variables or other resources with each other, there are no concurrency hazards.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] The key advantage of RTC processing is simplicity.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Its biggest disadvantage is that the responsiveness of a state machine is determined by its longest RTC step.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Achieving short RTC steps can often significantly complicate real-time designs.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Though the traditional FSMs are an excellent tool for tackling smaller problems, it's also generally known that they tend to become unmanageable, even for moderately involved systems.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Due to the phenomenon known as **state and transition explosion**, the complexity of a traditional FSM tends to grow much faster than the complexity of the system it describes.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] This happens because the traditional state machine formalism inflicts repetitions.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] For example, if you try to represent the behavior of a simple pocket calculator with a traditional FSM, you'll immediately notice that many events (e.g., the Clear or Off button presses) are handled identically in many states.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] A conventional FSM shown in the figure below, has no means of capturing such a commonality and requires *repeating* the same actions and transitions in many states.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] What's missing in the traditional state machines is the mechanism for factoring out the common behavior in order to share it across many states.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] UML state machines address exactly this shortcoming of the conventional FSMs.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] They provide a number of features for eliminating the repetitions so that the complexity of a UML state machine no longer explodes but tends to faithfully represent the complexity of the reactive system it describes.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Obviously, these features are very interesting to software developers, because only they make the whole state machine approach truly applicable to real-life problems.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] The most important innovation of UML state machines over the traditional FSMs is the introduction of **hierarchically nested states** (that is why statecharts are also called **hierarchical state machines**, or **HSM**s).
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] The semantics associated with state nesting are as follows (see Figure 3): If a system is in the nested state, for example "result" (called the **substate**), it also (implicitly) is in the surrounding state "on" (called the **superstate**).
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] This state machine will attempt to handle any event in the context of the substate, which conceptually is at the lower level of the hierarchy.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] However, if the substate "result" does not prescribe how to handle the event, the event is not quietly discarded as in a traditional "flat" state machine; rather, it is automatically handled at the higher level context of the superstate "on".
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] This is what is meant by the system being in state "result" as well as "on".
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Of course, state nesting is not limited to one level only, and the simple rule of event processing applies recursively to any level of nesting.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] States that contain other states are called *composite states*; conversely, states without internal structure are called *simple states*.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] A nested state is called a *direct substate* when it is not contained by any other state; otherwise, it is referred to as a *transitively nested substate*.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Because the internal structure of a composite state can be arbitrarily complex, any hierarchical state machine can be viewed as an internal structure of some (higher-level) composite state.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] It is conceptually convenient to define one composite state as the ultimate root of state machine hierarchy.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] In the UML specification, every state machine has a **region** (the abstract root of every state machine hierarchy), which contains all the other elements of the entire state machine.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] The graphical rendering of this all-enclosing region is optional.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] As you can see, the semantics of hierarchical state decomposition are designed to facilitate reusing of behavior.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] The substates (nested states) need only define the differences from the superstates (containing states).
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] A substate can easily inherit the common behavior from its superstate(s) by simply ignoring commonly handled events, which are then automatically handled by higher-level states.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] In other words, hierarchical state nesting enables **programming by difference**.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] The aspect of state hierarchy emphasized most often is abstraction—an old and powerful technique for coping with complexity.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Instead of addressing all aspects of a complex system at the same time, it is often possible to ignore (abstract away) some parts of the system.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Hierarchical states are an ideal mechanism for hiding internal details because the designer can easily zoom out or zoom in to hide or show nested states.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] However, composite states don't simply hide complexity; they also actively reduce it through the powerful mechanism of hierarchical event processing.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Without such reuse, even a moderate increase in system complexity could lead to an explosive increase in the number of states and transitions.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] For example, the hierarchical state machine representing the pocket calculator (Figure 3) avoids repeating the transitions Clear and Off in virtually every state.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Avoiding repetition allows the growth of HSMs to remain proportionate to growth in system complexity.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] As the modeled system grows, the opportunity for reuse also increases and thus potentially counteracts the disproportionate increase in numbers of states and transitions typical of traditional FSMs.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Analysis by hierarchical state decomposition can include the application of the operation 'exclusive-OR' to any given state.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] For example, if a system is in the "on" superstate (Figure 3), it may be the case that it is also in either "operand1" substate OR the "operand2" substate OR the "opEntered" substate OR the "result" substate.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] This would lead to description of the "on" superstate as an 'OR-state'.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] UML statecharts also introduce the complementary AND-decomposition.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Such decomposition means that a composite state can contain two or more orthogonal regions (orthogonal means compatible and independent in this context) and that being in such a composite state entails being in all its orthogonal regions simultaneously.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Orthogonal regions address the frequent problem of a combinatorial increase in the number of states when the behavior of a system is fragmented into independent, concurrently active parts.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] For example, apart from the main keypad, a computer keyboard has an independent numeric keypad.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] From the previous discussion, recall the two states of the main keypad already identified: "default" and "caps_locked" (see Figure 1).
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] The numeric keypad also can be in two states—"numbers" and "arrows"—depending on whether Num Lock is active.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] The use of orthogonal regions allows the mixing of independent behaviors as a Cartesian product to be avoided and, instead, for them to remain separate, as shown in Figure 4.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] However, the general case of mutual dependency, on the other hand, results in multiplicative complexity, so in general, the number of states needed is the product *k × l × m × ...*.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] In most real-life situations, orthogonal regions would be only approximately orthogonal (i.e. not truly independent).
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Therefore, UML statecharts provide a number of ways for orthogonal regions to communicate and synchronize their behaviors.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Among these rich sets of (sometimes complex) mechanisms, perhaps the most important feature is that orthogonal regions can coordinate their behaviors by sending event instances to each other.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Even though orthogonal regions imply independence of execution (allowing more or less concurrency), the UML specification does not require that a separate thread of execution be assigned to each orthogonal region (although this can be done if desired).
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] In fact, most commonly, orthogonal regions execute within the same thread.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] The UML specification requires only that the designer does not rely on any particular order for event instances to be dispatched to the relevant orthogonal regions.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Every state in a UML statechart can have optional **entry actions**, which are executed upon entry to a state, as well as optional **exit actions**, which are executed upon exit from a state.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Entry and exit actions are associated with states, not transitions.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Regardless of how a state is entered or exited, all its entry and exit actions will be executed.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Because of this characteristic, statecharts behave like Moore machines.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] The UML notation for state entry and exit actions is to place the reserved word "entry" (or "exit") in the state right below the name compartment, followed by the forward slash and the list of arbitrary actions (see Figure 5).
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] The value of entry and exit actions is that they provide means for *guaranteed initialization and cleanup*, very much like class constructors and destructors in Object-oriented programming.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] For example, consider the "door_open" state from Figure 5, which corresponds to the toaster oven behavior while the door is open.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] This state has a very important safety-critical requirement: Always disable the heater when the door is open.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Additionally, while the door is open, the internal lamp illuminating the oven should light up.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Of course, such behavior could be modeled by adding appropriate actions (disabling the heater and turning on the light) to every transition path leading to the "door_open" state (the user may open the door at any time during "baking" or "toasting" or when the oven is not used at all).
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] It should not be forgotten to extinguish the internal lamp with every transition leaving the "door_open" state.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] However, such a solution would cause the repetition of actions in many transitions.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] More importantly, such an approach leaves the design error-prone during subsequent amendments to behavior (e.g., the next programmer working on a new feature, such as top-browning, might simply forget to disable the heater on transition to "door_open").
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Entry and exit actions allow implementation of desired behavior in a safer, simpler, and more intuitive way.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] As shown in Figure 5, it could be specified that the exit action from "heating" disables the heater, the entry action to "door_open" lights up the oven lamp, and the exit action from "door_open" extinguishes the lamp.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] The use of entry and exit actions is preferable to placing an action on a transition because it avoids repetitive coding and improves function by eliminating a safety hazard; (heater on while door open).
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] The semantics of exit actions guarantees that, regardless of the transition path, the heater will be disabled when the toaster is not in the "heating" state.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Because entry actions are executed automatically whenever an associated state is entered, they often determine the conditions of operation or the identity of the state, very much as a class constructor determines the identity of the object being constructed.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] For example, the identity of the "heating" state is determined by the fact that the heater is turned on.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] This condition must be established before entering any substate of "heating" because entry actions to a substate of "heating," like "toasting," rely on proper initialization of the "heating" superstate and perform only the differences from this initialization.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Consequently, the order of execution of entry actions must always proceed from the outermost state to the innermost state (top-down).
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Not surprisingly, this order is analogous to the order in which class constructors are invoked.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Construction of a class always starts at the very root of the class hierarchy and follows through all inheritance levels down to the class being instantiated.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] The execution of exit actions, which corresponds to destructor invocation, proceeds in the exact reverse order (bottom-up).
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Very commonly, an event causes only some internal actions to execute but does not lead to a change of state (state transition).
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] In this case, all actions executed comprise the **internal transition**.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] For example, when one types on a keyboard, it responds by generating different character codes.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] However, unless the Caps Lock key is pressed, the state of the keyboard does not change (no state transition occurs).
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] In UML, this situation should be modeled with internal transitions, as shown in Figure 6.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] The UML notation for internal transitions follows the general syntax used for exit (or entry) actions, except instead of the word entry (or exit) the internal transition is labeled with the triggering event (e.g., see the internal transition triggered by the ANY_KEY event in Figure 6).
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] In the absence of entry and exit actions, internal transitions would be identical to **self-transitions** (transitions in which the target state is the same as the source state).
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] In fact, in a classical Mealy machine, actions are associated exclusively with state transitions, so the only way to execute actions without changing state is through a self-transition (depicted as a directed loop in Figure 1 from the top of this article).
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] However, in the presence of entry and exit actions, as in UML statecharts, a self-transition involves the execution of exit and entry actions and therefore it is distinctively different from an internal transition.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] In contrast to a self-transition, no entry or exit actions are ever executed as a result of an internal transition, even if the internal transition is inherited from a higher level of the hierarchy than the currently active state.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Internal transitions inherited from superstates at any level of nesting act as if they were defined directly in the currently active state.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] State nesting combined with entry and exit actions significantly complicates the state transition semantics in HSMs compared to the traditional FSMs.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] When dealing with hierarchically nested states and orthogonal regions, the simple term *current state* can be quite confusing.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] In an HSM, more than one state can be active at once.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] If the state machine is in a leaf state that is contained in a composite state (which is possibly contained in a higher-level composite state, and so on), all the composite states that either directly or transitively contain the leaf state are also active.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Furthermore, because some of the composite states in this hierarchy might have orthogonal regions, the current active state is actually represented by a tree of states starting with the single region at the root down to individual simple states at the leaves.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] The UML specification refers to such a state tree as state configuration.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] In UML, a state transition can directly connect any two states.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] These two states, which may be composite, are designated as the **main source** and the **main target** of a transition.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Figure 7 shows a simple transition example and explains the state roles in that transition.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Execute the actions associated with the transition.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] The transition sequence is easy to interpret in the simple case of both the main source and the main target nesting at the same level.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] For example, transition T1 shown in Figure 7 causes the evaluation of the guard g(); followed by the sequence of actions: `a(); b(); t(); c(); d();` and `e()`; assuming that the guard `g()` evaluates to TRUE.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] However, in the general case of source and target states nested at different levels of the state hierarchy, it might not be immediately obvious how many levels of nesting need to be exited.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] The UML specification prescribes that a transition involves exiting all nested states from the current active state (which might be a direct or transitive substate of the main source state) up to, but not including, the **least common ancestor** (LCA) state of the main source and main target states.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] As the name indicates, the LCA is the lowest composite state that is simultaneously a superstate (ancestor) of both the source and the target states.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] As described before, the order of execution of exit actions is always from the most deeply nested state (the current active state) up the hierarchy to the LCA but without exiting the LCA.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Entering the target state configuration commences from the level where the exit actions left off (i.e., from inside the LCA).
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] As described before, entry actions must be executed starting from the highest-level state down the state hierarchy to the main target state.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] If the main target state is composite, the UML semantics prescribes to "drill" into its submachine recursively using the local initial transitions.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] The target state configuration is completely entered only after encountering a leaf state that has no initial transitions.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Before UML 2, the only transition semantics in use was the **external transition**, in which the main source of the transition is always exited and the main target of the transition is always entered.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] UML 2 preserved the "external transition" semantics for backward compatibility, but introduced also a new kind of transition called **local transition** (see Section 14.2.3.4.4 of *Unified Modeling Language (UML)*).
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] For many transition topologies, external and local transitions are actually identical.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] However, a local transition doesn't cause exit from and reentry to the main source state if the main target state is a substate of the main source.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] In addition, a local state transition doesn't cause exit from and reentry to the main target state if the main target is a superstate of the main source state.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Figure 8 contrasts local (a) and external (b) transitions.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] In the top row, you see the case of the main source containing the main target.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] The local transition does not cause exit from the source, while the external transition causes exit and reentry to the source.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] In the bottom row of Figure 8, you see the case of the main target containing the main source.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] The local transition does not cause entry to the target, whereas the external transition causes exit and reentry to the target.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Sometimes an event arrives at a particularly inconvenient time, when a state machine is in a state that cannot handle the event.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] In many cases, the nature of the event is such that it can be postponed (within limits) until the system enters another state, in which it is better prepared to handle the original event.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] UML state machines provide a special mechanism for **deferring events** in states.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] In every state, you can include a clause `[event list]/defer`.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] If an event in the current state's deferred event list occurs, the event will be saved (deferred) for future processing until a state is entered that does not list the event in its deferred event list.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Upon entry to such a state, the UML state machine will automatically recall any saved event(s) that are no longer deferred and will then either consume or discard these events.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] It is possible for a superstate to have a transition defined on an event that is deferred by a substate.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Consistent with other areas in the specification of UML state machines, the substate takes precedence over the superstate, the event will be deferred and the transition for the superstate will not be executed.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] In the case of orthogonal regions where one orthogonal region defers an event and another consumes the event, the consumer takes precedence and the event is consumed and not deferred.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Harel statecharts, which are the precursors of UML state machines, have been invented as "a visual formalism for complex systems", so from their inception, they have been inseparably associated with graphical representation in the form of state diagrams.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] However, it is important to understand that the concept of UML state machine transcends any particular notation, graphical or textual.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] The UML specification makes this distinction apparent by clearly separating state machine semantics from the notation.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] However, the notation of UML statecharts is not purely visual.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Any nontrivial state machine requires a large amount of textual information (e.g., the specification of actions and guards).
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] The exact syntax of action and guard expressions isn't defined in the UML specification, so many people use either structured English or, more formally, expressions in an implementation language such as C, C++, or Java.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] In practice, this means that UML statechart notation depends heavily on the specific programming language.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Nevertheless, most of the statecharts semantics are heavily biased toward graphical notation.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] For example, state diagrams poorly represent the sequence of processing, be it order of evaluation of guards or order of dispatching events to orthogonal regions.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] The UML specification sidesteps these problems by putting the burden on the designer not to rely on any particular sequencing.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] However, it is the case that when UML state machines are actually implemented, there is inevitably full control over order of execution, giving rise to criticism that the UML semantics may be unnecessarily restrictive.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] Similarly, statechart diagrams require a lot of plumbing gear (pseudostates, like joins, forks, junctions, choicepoints, etc.) to represent the flow of control graphically.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] In other words, these elements of the graphical notation do not add much value in representing flow of control as compared to plain structured code.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] The UML notation and semantics are really geared toward computerized UML tools.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] A UML state machine, as represented in a tool, is not just the state diagram, but rather a mixture of graphical and textual representation that precisely captures both the state topology and the actions.
[src:finite-state-machine-ai/uml-state-machine] The users of the tool can get several complementary views of the same state machine, both visual and textual, whereas the generated code is just one of the many available views.
